</p><p>A laud to frankness, the cardinal Epicurean virtue of ''parrhesia'': it is best to speak of natural matters frankly (i.e. in a manner that is void of any [[superstition]]) than to cater to popular beliefs, however false those might be, in order to garner the applause that the multitudes are so ready to confer upon anyone who agrees with their prejudices.
</p>
The paradoxical argument is that this, rather anti-populist position the true philosopher ought to assume, ultimately is the one that is indeed beneficial to all people. It is better to speak in a manner that seems "oracular" and might not be understood by many, rather than to take the facile approach of consenting to all sorts of popular misconceptions.'><font color='#800000'>popular</font></a>&nbsp;</p><br><p><a href='http://wiki.epicurism.info/iurl/index.php?title=Template:GED:popular&amp;action=edit'><font color='#cc6600'>edit</font></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p></span><span><p class='script150'><a href='http://wiki.epicurism.info/iurl/index.php?title=Template:GED:misconceptions' title='Dictionary empty: use link below:/→,2:/→,3:/I for sure [would rather want],4:/→,5:/while discussing nature [frankly],7:/→,8:/(of what is) beneficial (for),10:people,11:/→,12:/→,13:/→,14:even if,17:/comprehend,18:than,20:/to,21:/(popular) beliefs,22:to reap,23:the,24:/frequent [applause],25:/that comes from,26:/→,27:the,28:many,29:/→</interlinear>
<p>== Translation ==
</p><p><big>{{Vatican Saying 29}}</big>
</p><p>== Analysis ==
</p><p>A laud to frankness, the cardinal Epicurean virtue of ''parrhesia'': it is best to speak of natural matters frankly (i.e. in a manner that is void of any [[superstition]]) than to cater to popular beliefs, however false those might be, in order to garner the applause that the multitudes are so ready to confer upon anyone who agrees with their prejudices.
</p>
The paradoxical argument is that this, rather anti-populist position the true philosopher ought to assume, ultimately is the one that is indeed beneficial to all people. It is better to speak in a manner that seems "oracular" and might not be understood by many, rather than to take the facile approach of consenting to all sorts of popular misconceptions.'><font color='#800000'>misconceptions.</font></a>&nbsp;</p><br><p><a href='http://wiki.epicurism.info/iurl/index.php?title=Template:GED:misconceptions&amp;action=edit'><font color='#cc6600'>edit</font></a>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p></span><span><p><a href='http://wiki.epicurism.info/iurl/index.php?title=template:Vatican Saying 29 Text' title='Vatican Saying 29 Text'><img src='http://www.epicurus.info/scroll.gif'></a></p></span></div>
<a name="Translation"></a><h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/iurl/index.php?title=Vatican_Saying_29&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Translation">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"> Translation </span></h2>
<p><big><a href="/iurl/index.php?title=Template:Vatican_Saying_29&amp;action=edit" class="new" title="Template:Vatican Saying 29">Template:Vatican Saying 29</a></big>
</p>
<a name="Analysis"></a><h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/iurl/index.php?title=Vatican_Saying_29&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Analysis">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline"> Analysis </span></h2>
<p>A laud to frankness, the cardinal Epicurean virtue of <i>parrhesia</i>: it is best to speak of natural matters frankly (i.e. in a manner that is void of any <a href="/Superstition" title="Superstition">superstition</a>) than to cater to popular beliefs, however false those might be, in order to garner the applause that the multitudes are so ready to confer upon anyone who agrees with their prejudices.
</p><p>The paradoxical argument is that this, rather anti-populist position the true philosopher ought to assume, ultimately is the one that is indeed beneficial to all people. It is better to speak in a manner that seems "oracular" and might not be understood by many, rather than to take the facile approach of consenting to all sorts of popular misconceptions.
</p><div class="printfooter">
